\[ \text{KE}_{\text{avg}} = \frac{1}{2} m v^2 \]

where \( m \) is the mass of the particle and \( v \) is the average speed of the particle.

For Sample A:
- Mass of each particle (\( m_A \)) = 30 u
- Average particle speed (\( v_A \)) = 1,400 m/s

\[ \text{KE}_{\text{avg, A}} = \frac{1}{2} \times 30 \, \text{u} \times (1,400 \, \text{m/s})^2 \]

For Sample B:

- Average particle speed (\( v_B \)) = 1,400 m/s

\[ \text{KE}_{\text{avg, B}} = \frac{1}{2} \times 32 \, \text{u} \times (1,400 \, \text{m/s})^2 \]

Since both samples have the same average particle speed, the kinetic energy will be directly proportional to the mass of the particles. Therefore, we can compare the kinetic energies by comparing the masses:

\[ \text{KE}_{\text{avg, A}} = \frac{1}{2} \times 30 \, \text{u} \times (1,400 \, \text{m/s})^2 \]
\[ \text{KE}_{\text{avg, B}} = \frac{1}{2} \times 32 \, \text{u} \times (1,400 \, \text{m/s})^2 \]

Since 30 u < 32 u, it follows that:

\[ \text{KE}_{\text{avg, A}} < \text{KE}_{\text{avg, B}} \]

Thus, the average kinetic energy of the particles in Sample B is greater than that in Sample A. Since temperature is directly related to the average kinetic energy of the particles, Sample B has a higher temperature than Sample A.
